Note:
============================================================================
THREADING SUPPORT WRAPPERS (P2-B.2)
SRWLOCK, CONDITION_VARIABLE, ExitThread, SwitchToThread, SetThreadDescription,
CreateSemaphore, ReleaseSemaphore, GetSystemInfo. All target kernel32.dll
(SRWLOCK / CONDITION_VARIABLE entry points are present in kernel32 on
Windows Vista and later; GetSystemInfo is present on all NT versions).
Microsoft Win32 API documentation:
  https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/
  https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/
  https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/sysinfoapi/
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "windows_arm64_api_exit_thread" takes exit_code as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    ExitThread - terminate the calling thread with the supplied DWORD
    exit code. Used by Runa's thread_exit primitive to cleanly tear down
    a worker thread without unwinding the stack frame that launched it.
    Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-exitthread)
    ExitThread runs all thread-attached DLL detach routines, flushes
    Fiber-Local Storage destructors, releases the thread's stack, and
    signals the thread handle. Unlike TerminateThread it does NOT leak
    thread-local destructors.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call. Microsoft ARM64 ABI passes the DWORD exit_code in
    X0. The function does not return; the post-call store exists only
    for code-shape symmetry with other api_* wrappers - control transfers
    to the Windows scheduler when ExitThread tears the thread down.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One library call; the thread leaves the run queue after kernel32
    teardown. No syscall fast path - ExitThread always runs DllMain
    DLL_THREAD_DETACH notifications.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the calling thread; the process and sibling threads
    are unaffected. No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load DWORD exit_code into X0 (Microsoft ARM64 ABI 1st arg)
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]

        # Call ExitThread from kernel32.dll
        bl ExitThread

        # ExitThread is __declspec(noreturn); this store exists only for
        # symmetry with other api_* wrappers.
        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_switch_to_thread" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    SwitchToThread - yield the remainder of the calling thread's
    scheduling quantum to another ready thread on the same processor.
    Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-switchtothread)
    distinguishes this from Sleep(0): SwitchToThread restricts the
    candidate set to threads on the SAME processor. For thread_yield in
    Runa's cooperative spin-wait paths this is the cheaper option.
    Returns nonzero if a context switch occurred, zero if no other ready
    thread was available.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Zero-argument Win32 call. Result returned in X0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sub-microsecond when another runnable thread exists; near-zero when
    the run queue is empty.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privilege change.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # No arguments to marshal
        bl SwitchToThread

        # Store BOOL result from X0
        str x0, [sp, #-8]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_set_thread_description" takes thread_handle as Integer, description_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    SetThreadDescription - attach a human-readable wide-character name
    to a thread, observable in debuggers, performance tools, and ETW
    traces. Available on Windows 10 1607+ via kernel32.dll
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/processthreadsapi/nf-processthreadsapi-setthreaddescription).
    Used by Runa's thread_set_name primitive.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-argument Win32 call. Microsoft ARM64 ABI passes thread_handle in
    X0 and LPCWSTR description in X1. Returns HRESULT (S_OK = 0 on
    success, negative on failure - test with FAILED() / SUCCEEDED()).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One library call; kernel32 stores the description in the thread's
    TEB / kernel thread object. Sub-microsecond cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Requires THREAD_SET_LIMITED_INFORMATION (0x0400) access on the
    target thread handle.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]      # thread_handle (1st parameter)
        ldr x1, [sp, #-16]     # description_ptr (2nd parameter)

        bl SetThreadDescription

        str x0, [sp, #-24]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_initialize_srwlock" takes lock_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    InitializeSRWLock - initialize a Slim Reader/Writer lock to its
    released, no-waiters state. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializesrwlock)
    the lock is a single pointer-sized opaque value; the function
    simply zeroes that pointer (RTL_SRWLOCK_INIT). Used by Runa's
    mutex_create and rwlock_create.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call; PSRWLOCK passed in X0; void return - result is
    forced to 0 for Runa Process-signature conformance.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sub-100ns; effectively a memory write of zero to the lock word.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]      # lock_ptr (1st parameter)

        bl InitializeSRWLock

        # Returns void; force result = 0
        mov x0, #0
        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_acquire_srwlock_exclusive" takes lock_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    AcquireSRWLockExclusive - block the calling thread until the SRWLOCK
    can be acquired in exclusive (writer) mode. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-acquiresrwlockexclusive)
    the SRWLOCK provides a far smaller footprint than a CRITICAL_SECTION
    (single pointer vs 40 bytes) and a faster uncontended path. Used as
    the underlying primitive for Runa's mutex_lock.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call; PSRWLOCK in X0; void return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended acquire is ~10 ns. SRWLOCK is non-recursive; re-entering
    from the holder thread is undefined behaviour.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]

        bl AcquireSRWLockExclusive

        mov x0, #0
        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_release_srwlock_exclusive" takes lock_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    ReleaseSRWLockExclusive - release an SRWLOCK held in exclusive
    (writer) mode. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-releasesrwlockexclusive)
    pairs 1:1 with AcquireSRWLockExclusive; releasing a lock not held
    exclusively is undefined behaviour.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call; PSRWLOCK in X0; void return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended release is ~5 ns.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must hold the lock exclusively.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]

        bl ReleaseSRWLockExclusive

        mov x0, #0
        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_try_acquire_srwlock_exclusive" takes lock_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    TryAcquireSRWLockExclusive - non-blocking variant of
    AcquireSRWLockExclusive. Returns BOOLEAN TRUE on success, FALSE if a
    contender holds the lock. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-tryacquiresrwlockexclusive)
    succeeds atomically without descending into the kernel. Used by
    Runa's mutex_try_lock.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call; PSRWLOCK in X0; BOOLEAN return in W0/X0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single atomic cmpxchg; constant time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]

        bl TryAcquireSRWLockExclusive

        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_acquire_srwlock_shared" takes lock_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    AcquireSRWLockShared - acquire an SRWLOCK in shared (reader) mode.
    Multiple readers may hold the lock concurrently; writers wait for
    the reader count to drain. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-acquiresrwlockshared)
    pairs with ReleaseSRWLockShared. Used by Runa's rwlock_read_lock.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call; PSRWLOCK in X0; void return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended path is ~10 ns; reader count incremented atomically.
    Contended path (writer queued) blocks the new reader.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]

        bl AcquireSRWLockShared

        mov x0, #0
        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_release_srwlock_shared" takes lock_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    ReleaseSRWLockShared - release a reader hold on an SRWLOCK. Per
    Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-releasesrwlockshared)
    decrements the reader count; if the count reaches zero with a writer
    queued, the writer is woken. Used by Runa's rwlock_unlock on the
    reader path.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call; PSRWLOCK in X0; void return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Atomic decrement plus optional wake; ~10 ns uncontended.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must hold the lock in shared mode.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]

        bl ReleaseSRWLockShared

        mov x0, #0
        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_try_acquire_srwlock_shared" takes lock_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    TryAcquireSRWLockShared - non-blocking shared-mode acquire. Per
    Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-tryacquiresrwlockshared)
    returns nonzero on success, zero if a writer holds or is queued.
    Used by Runa's rwlock_try_read_lock.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call; PSRWLOCK in X0; BOOLEAN return in W0/X0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single cmpxchg, constant time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]

        bl TryAcquireSRWLockShared

        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_create_semaphore" takes security_attributes as Integer, initial_count as Integer, maximum_count as Integer, name_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    CreateSemaphoreA - create a kernel-object counting semaphore. Per
    Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-createsemaphorea)
    the returned HANDLE is signalled while the internal count is greater
    than zero. WaitForSingleObject decrements the count by one when it
    succeeds; ReleaseSemaphore increments by a caller-supplied amount.
    Used by Runa's semaphore_create.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Four-argument Win32 call. Microsoft ARM64 ABI: X0 = security_attributes,
    X1 = initial_count, X2 = maximum_count, X3 = name_ptr (LPCSTR or
    NULL for anonymous). Returns HANDLE in X0 (0 on failure).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single kernel-object creation; ~10 microseconds typical. Anonymous
    semaphores (name_ptr = 0) avoid namespace lookup.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Anonymous semaphores are process-private. Named semaphores live in
    the kernel object namespace and may be inherited or duplicated
    across processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]      # security_attributes
        ldr x1, [sp, #-16]     # initial_count
        ldr x2, [sp, #-24]     # maximum_count
        ldr x3, [sp, #-32]     # name_ptr

        bl CreateSemaphoreA

        str x0, [sp, #-40]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_release_semaphore" takes semaphore_handle as Integer, release_count as Integer, previous_count_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    ReleaseSemaphore - increment the semaphore's internal count by the
    supplied amount, optionally returning the prior value through
    previous_count_ptr. Per Microsoft documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-releasesemaphore)
    fails (returns 0) if the new total would exceed maximum_count. Used
    by Runa's semaphore_signal.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-argument Win32 call. Microsoft ARM64 ABI: X0 = handle,
    X1 = release_count, X2 = previous_count_ptr (LPLONG or NULL).
    Returns BOOL.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single kernel transition; wakes at most release_count waiters.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must hold a valid handle with SEMAPHORE_MODIFY_STATE (0x0002)
    access.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]
        ldr x1, [sp, #-16]
        ldr x2, [sp, #-24]

        bl ReleaseSemaphore

        str x0, [sp, #-32]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_api_initialize_condition_variable" takes cv_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
