Process called "windows_arm64_api_get_system_info" takes system_info_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    GetSystemInfo - fill a SYSTEM_INFO structure with hardware and OS
    parameters: processor architecture, page size, processor count,
    allocation granularity, address-space bounds. Per Microsoft
    documentation
    (https://learn.microsoft.com/windows/win32/api/sysinfoapi/nf-sysinfoapi-getsysteminfo)
    the SYSTEM_INFO layout places dwNumberOfProcessors at offset 32
    (0x20) on 64-bit Windows. Used by Runa's hardware_concurrency
    primitive.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single Win32 call. Microsoft ARM64 ABI: X0 = LPSYSTEM_INFO. Returns
    void; caller reads fields from the supplied buffer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single library call; the result is internally cached by kernel32,
    so repeated calls are near-zero cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No privileges required. The buffer must be process-owned and at
    least 64 bytes for the canonical SYSTEM_INFO layout.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        ldr x0, [sp, #-8]

        bl GetSystemInfo

        mov x0, #0
        str x0, [sp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
HIGH-LEVEL WRAPPER FUNCTIONS
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for ReadFile
    fd: file handle (Windows uses handles, not file descriptors)
    buffer: pointer to buffer
    count: number of bytes to read
    Returns: number of bytes read, or -1 on error
    :End Note
    
    Let bytes_read_ptr be proc memory_alloc from Memory with 8
    Let result be windows_arm64_api_read_file(fd, buffer, count, bytes_read_ptr, 0)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        proc memory_free from Memory with bytes_read_ptr
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Let bytes_read be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with bytes_read_ptr, 0
    proc memory_free from Memory with bytes_read_ptr
    Return bytes_read
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for WriteFile
    fd: file handle (Windows uses handles, not file descriptors)
    buffer: pointer to buffer
    count: number of bytes to write
    Returns: number of bytes written, or -1 on error
    :End Note
    
    Let bytes_written_ptr be proc memory_alloc from Memory with 8
    Let result be windows_arm64_api_write_file(fd, buffer, count, bytes_written_ptr, 0)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        proc memory_free from Memory with bytes_written_ptr
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Let bytes_written be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with bytes_written_ptr, 0
    proc memory_free from Memory with bytes_written_ptr
    Return bytes_written
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for CreateFileW
    filename: pointer to wide string filename
    flags: access flags (O_RDONLY, O_WRONLY, O_RDWR)
    mode: creation mode (ignored on Windows)
    Returns: file handle or -1 on error
    :End Note
    
    Let desired_access be 0
    Let share_mode be windows_arm64_FILE_SHARE_READ plus windows_arm64_FILE_SHARE_WRITE
    Let creation_disposition be windows_arm64_OPEN_EXISTING
    Let flags_and_attributes be windows_arm64_FILE_ATTRIBUTE_NORMAL

    If flags is equal to 0:
        Set desired_access to windows_arm64_GENERIC_READ
    Otherwise If flags is equal to 1:
        Set desired_access to windows_arm64_GENERIC_WRITE
    Otherwise If flags is equal to 2:
        Set desired_access to windows_arm64_GENERIC_READ plus windows_arm64_GENERIC_WRITE
    End If

    Let handle be windows_arm64_api_create_file(filename, desired_access, share_mode, 0, creation_disposition, flags_and_attributes, 0)

    If handle is equal to windows_arm64_INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE:
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Return handle
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for CloseHandle
    fd: file handle
    Returns: 0 on success, -1 on error
    :End Note
    
    Let result be windows_arm64_api_close_handle(fd)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_exit" takes exit_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for TerminateProcess
    exit_code: exit code
    Returns: never returns (process terminates)
    :End Note
    
    Let current_process be windows_arm64_api_get_current_process()
    Let result be windows_arm64_api_terminate_process(current_process, exit_code)

    Return -1  Note: Should never reach here
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for VirtualAlloc
    addr: preferred address or 0
    length: size in bytes
    prot: protection flags
    flags: allocation flags (ignored)
    fd: file descriptor (ignored)
    offset: file offset (ignored)
    Returns: pointer to allocated memory or -1 on error
    :End Note
    
    Let allocation_type be windows_arm64_MEM_COMMIT
    Let protect be windows_arm64_PAGE_READWRITE

    If prot is equal to 1:
        Set protect to windows_arm64_PAGE_READONLY
    Otherwise If prot is equal to 2:
        Set protect to windows_arm64_PAGE_READWRITE
    Otherwise If prot is equal to 4:
        Set protect to windows_arm64_PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE
    End If

    Let result be windows_arm64_api_virtual_alloc(addr, length, allocation_type, protect)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Return result
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for VirtualFree
    addr: pointer to memory
    length: size in bytes (ignored, must be 0 for MEM_RELEASE)
    Returns: 0 on success, -1 on error
    :End Note
    
    Let result be windows_arm64_api_virtual_free(addr, 0, windows_arm64_MEM_RELEASE)
    
    If result is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_mprotect" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for VirtualProtect
    addr: pointer to memory
    length: size in bytes
    prot: new protection flags
    Returns: 0 on success, -1 on error
    :End Note
    
    Let old_protect_ptr be proc memory_alloc from Memory with 8
    Let new_protect be windows_arm64_PAGE_READWRITE

    If prot is equal to 1:
        Set new_protect to windows_arm64_PAGE_READONLY
    Otherwise If prot is equal to 2:
        Set new_protect to windows_arm64_PAGE_READWRITE
    Otherwise If prot is equal to 4:
        Set new_protect to windows_arm64_PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE
    End If

    Let result be windows_arm64_api_virtual_protect(addr, length, new_protect, old_protect_ptr)
    proc memory_free from Memory with old_protect_ptr
    
    If result is equal to 0:
    Return -1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_getpid" returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for GetCurrentProcessId
    Returns: process ID
    :End Note
    
    Return windows_arm64_api_get_current_process_id()
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_kill" takes pid as Integer, sig as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    High-level wrapper for TerminateProcess
    pid: process ID
    sig: signal number (used as exit code)
    Returns: 0 on success, -1 on error
    :End Note

    Note: Check if terminating current process
    If pid is equal to windows_arm64_api_get_current_process_id():
        Let current_process be windows_arm64_api_get_current_process()
        Let result be windows_arm64_api_terminate_process(current_process, sig)
        Return -1  Note: Should never reach here
    End If

    Note:
    Terminating another process - use OpenProcess
    PROCESS_TERMINATE = 0x0001
    :End Note
    Let desired_access be 1  Note: PROCESS_TERMINATE
    Let inherit_handle be 0  Note: FALSE

    Note: Call OpenProcess to get handle to target process
    Let process_handle be windows_arm64_api_open_process(desired_access, inherit_handle, pid)
    If process_handle is equal to 0:
        Return -1  Note: Failed to open process (access denied or invalid PID)
    End If

    Note: Terminate the process with signal as exit code
    Let terminate_result be windows_arm64_api_terminate_process(process_handle, sig)

    Note: Close process handle
    windows_arm64_api_close_handle(process_handle)

    Note: Check if termination succeeded
    If terminate_result is equal to 0:
        Return -1  Note: TerminateProcess failed
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Success
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
WINDOWS-SYNTHESIZED DISPATCHER FILE I/O WRAPPERS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher (assembly/syscall.runa, idx=15 for
windows_arm64) exposes three additional bare-name file-I/O wrappers that
the Unix-derived dispatcher API requires: syscall_brk, syscall_fstat,
syscall_lseek. None of these have a direct Win32 equivalent — Windows
manages process heap via the dedicated heap-API (HeapCreate/HeapAlloc)
and address space via VirtualAlloc, and Win32 uses GetFileSizeEx /
GetFileInformationByHandle / SetFilePointerEx in place of the Unix
fstat / lseek pair. To keep the 66-name dispatched contract uniform
across all 18 platforms (P2-B Decision 5, "Per-platform syscall
inventory"), these three wrappers are synthesized on Windows as
shape-preserving sentinels:

- syscall_brk: Windows has no `brk(2)` equivalent. The Win32 process
  uses VirtualAlloc/VirtualFree (already exposed via api_virtual_alloc
  / api_virtual_free and the syscall_mmap / syscall_munmap wrappers).
  Calling syscall_brk on Windows is a portability error in caller
  code; the wrapper returns -1 so the caller's standard
  errno-or-negative check fires. Per P2-B Decision 4, Windows callers
  should use syscall_mmap (which routes to VirtualAlloc) instead.

- syscall_fstat: Windows uses GetFileInformationByHandle which returns
  a BY_HANDLE_FILE_INFORMATION structure that is NOT layout-compatible
  with the Unix `struct stat`. Win32-native paths are FFI-tier (Phase 8);
  this stub returns -1 to preserve cross-platform link-graph closure.
  Per P2-B Decision 4 the shape-preserving sentinel is correct for
  compile-time dispatcher conformance.

- syscall_lseek: Windows uses SetFilePointerEx with a LARGE_INTEGER
  distance. Win32-native paths are FFI-tier (Phase 8); this stub returns
  -1 to preserve cross-platform link-graph closure. Per P2-B Decision 4,
  the sentinel preserves the dispatcher contract.

Sources:
- Microsoft Learn — "Memory Management Functions" (no brk equivalent).
- Microsoft Learn — `GetFileInformationByHandle` and
  `BY_HANDLE_FILE_INFORMATION` (layout differs from Unix `struct stat`).
- Microsoft Learn — `SetFilePointerEx` (LARGE_INTEGER signature, no
  Unix-equivalent SEEK_SET/CUR/END encoding — the synthesized constants
  SEEK_SET=0, SEEK_CUR=1, SEEK_END=2 are mapped to FILE_BEGIN, FILE_CURRENT,
  FILE_END respectively in the future FFI path; the values coincidentally
  match).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper returns -1 (the cross-platform errno sentinel) so that
the standard `If result < 0` failure-check pattern in caller code
behaves correctly. The argument lists match the Unix-side signatures
exactly so the dispatcher can resolve calls without arity mismatch.

These are NOT dead code: the dispatcher (assembly/syscall.runa)
hard-routes idx=15 calls to `windows_arm64_syscall_brk`, etc., once
Wave 2 (Decision 5 rename) and Wave 3 (Decision 1 dispatcher rewrite)
land. Removing them breaks the dispatcher's compile-time link graph
closure (P2-B Gate C / Gate D), which is the entire reason the
59-name backfill exists.

The bodies are intentionally minimal: a single `Return -1`. There is
no inline assembly because there is no kernel32 routine to call on
Windows that satisfies the Unix semantic; deferring the real Win32-
specific implementation to the FFI pass is the architecturally
correct choice (P2-B Decision 4, Open Question 4).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
These wrappers compile to a single mov-immediate / return pair. The
compiler is expected to inline them at every call site, leaving zero
call overhead.

If a Windows-targeting caller hits one of these wrappers in a hot
path, the correct optimisation is to switch to the Win32-native
equivalent: api_virtual_alloc / api_virtual_free for memory sizing,
api_get_file_information_by_handle (future FFI) for file metadata,
api_set_file_pointer_ex (future FFI) for file positioning. The
sentinel itself is so cheap that callers won't measure it as a hot
spot in any realistic workload.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The sentinel return value (-1) is the standard Unix-errno-on-failure
convention. Callers that fail to check the return value before using
it as a meaningful syscall result will dereference -1 / treat it as
a count / address, which is a classic source of memory-safety bugs.
This is no different from any other syscall wrapper in the file; the
caller's responsibility for return-value checking is unchanged.

These wrappers do NOT leak any state, do NOT touch any kernel
object, do NOT mutate any process resource. They are pure functions
returning -1. The security surface is therefore zero beyond the
caller's already-required return-value check.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Windows has no brk(2) equivalent; callers should use syscall_mmap
    (which routes to VirtualAlloc) for heap-style allocation on Windows.
    addr: ignored on Windows
    Returns: -1 (operation not supported on Windows)
    :End Note
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Windows uses GetFileInformationByHandle which returns a
    BY_HANDLE_FILE_INFORMATION not layout-compatible with Unix struct stat.
    Win32-native paths are FFI-tier (Phase 8); this stub returns -1 to
    preserve cross-platform link-graph closure.
    fd: ignored on Windows
    statbuf: ignored on Windows
    Returns: -1 (operation not supported on Windows; use Win32-native path)
    :End Note
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Windows uses SetFilePointerEx with a LARGE_INTEGER distance.
    Win32-native paths are FFI-tier (Phase 8); this stub returns -1 to
    preserve cross-platform link-graph closure.
    fd: ignored on Windows
    offset: ignored on Windows
    whence: ignored on Windows
    Returns: -1 (operation not supported on Windows; use Win32-native path)
    :End Note
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for ioctl-equivalent device control on
    Windows aarch64. There is no NT syscall for ioctl(2); the
    semantic equivalent is the Win32 DeviceIoControl user-mode API,
    which forwards to NtDeviceIoControlFile. POSIX request codes
    (TCGETS, TIOCGWINSZ, FIONREAD, ...) have no one-to-one mapping
    to Win32 CTL_CODE-encoded IOCTL codes. The arm64 Windows port
    shares this contract with windows_x86_64 because the NT syscall
    surface is architecture-portable at the semantic level.

    Returns the -1 sentinel to signal "use the higher-level
    api_device_io_control or the platform-specific GetConsoleMode
    path". console_primitive's TTY-detection path treats the
    sentinel as "not a TTY" on Windows; the Windows-specific TTY
    check uses GetConsoleMode through api_* instead.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the -1 sentinel unconditionally. No syscall is invoked,
    no Win32 API call is made — translation responsibility lies
    with the caller, which must dispatch on the platform identity
    of the active backend before invoking ioctl-style operations.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return; inlinable. Code paths that branch
    on the -1 sentinel pay one compare-and-branch on the Windows
    target and zero overhead on POSIX targets.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No security surface. The -1 sentinel cannot be misused; callers
    that route to api_device_io_control are responsible for
    validating the HANDLE and the CTL_CODE-encoded request, and
    DeviceIoControl enforces the Windows ACL / driver-IOCTL access
    model.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return -1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
WINDOWS-SYNTHESIZED UNIX-STYLE DISPATCHER CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher requires 22 Unix-style constants
that Windows does not natively define: O_RDONLY/O_WRONLY/O_RDWR/O_CREAT/
O_TRUNC/O_APPEND (open(2) flags), PROT_NONE/READ/WRITE/EXEC (mmap(2)
memory protection), MAP_SHARED/PRIVATE/FIXED/ANONYMOUS (mmap(2) mapping
flags), SEEK_SET/CUR/END (lseek(2) whence), STDIN_FILENO/STDOUT_FILENO/
STDERR_FILENO (Unix file-descriptor-zero convention), MODE_0644/0755
(POSIX permission mode constants).

Per the P2-B design doc (line 242): "Windows: not applicable — file
flags are GENERIC_READ etc. ... The dispatcher's O_RDONLY etc. names
must be synthesized on Windows: each returns the equivalent Win32
dwDesiredAccess bit (GENERIC_READ=0x80000000 for O_RDONLY). Caller
code that uses O_* symbols becomes Windows-portable automatically via
this synthesis."

Synthesis policy (the values are NOT the Linux generic values; they
are the Win32 equivalents that make the bare-name dispatcher route
correctly on Windows):

- O_RDONLY → GENERIC_READ = 0x80000000
- O_WRONLY → GENERIC_WRITE = 0x40000000
- O_RDWR → GENERIC_READ | GENERIC_WRITE = 0xC0000000
- O_CREAT → 1 (semantic tag; Windows uses dwCreationDisposition
  CREATE_ALWAYS / OPEN_ALWAYS in the api_create_file path. The
  syscall_open wrapper translates the O_CREAT bit pattern to the
  matching CreateDisposition flag.)
- O_TRUNC → 2 (semantic tag; mapped to TRUNCATE_EXISTING in the
  api_create_file path.)
- O_APPEND → 4 (semantic tag; the file-append behaviour on Windows
  is achieved with FILE_APPEND_DATA in the desired-access mask. The
  syscall_open wrapper translates this bit.)
- PROT_NONE → 0x01 (synthesized; PAGE_NOACCESS=1 in the api_virtual_*
  path)
- PROT_READ → 0x02 (synthesized; PAGE_READONLY=2)
- PROT_WRITE → 0x04 (synthesized; PAGE_READWRITE=4)
- PROT_EXEC → 0x10 (synthesized; PAGE_EXECUTE=16)
- MAP_SHARED → 0x4000000 (synthesized; no direct Win32 equivalent;
  the syscall_mmap wrapper treats this as "shared mapping, currently
  unsupported on Windows" and returns -1 if set)
- MAP_PRIVATE → 0 (the default Win32 VirtualAlloc behaviour is
  private to the calling process)
- MAP_FIXED → 1 (synthesized; the syscall_mmap wrapper passes the
  requested address as the lpAddress parameter when this is set)
- MAP_ANONYMOUS → 0x40 (synthesized; the default behaviour of
  VirtualAlloc when no backing file is supplied)
- SEEK_SET → 0 (matches Win32 FILE_BEGIN=0)
- SEEK_CUR → 1 (matches Win32 FILE_CURRENT=1)
- SEEK_END → 2 (matches Win32 FILE_END=2)
- STDIN_FILENO → -10 (matches Win32 STD_INPUT_HANDLE=-10)
- STDOUT_FILENO → -11 (matches Win32 STD_OUTPUT_HANDLE=-11)
- STDERR_FILENO → -12 (matches Win32 STD_ERROR_HANDLE=-12)
- MODE_0644 → 420 (decimal of 0o644; ignored on Windows because file
  permissions use the security-descriptor model, but kept for source
  compatibility with Unix-derived caller code)
- MODE_0755 → 493 (decimal of 0o755; ignored on Windows for the same
  reason)

The STD*_FILENO synthesis re-uses the same numeric values as Win32's
STD_INPUT_HANDLE / STD_OUTPUT_HANDLE / STD_ERROR_HANDLE (already
defined above) so caller code using either name resolves to the same
integer.

Sources:
- Microsoft Learn — `CreateFile` (dwDesiredAccess values, GENERIC_*).
- Microsoft Learn — `VirtualAlloc` (PAGE_* constants).
- Microsoft Learn — `SetFilePointerEx` (FILE_BEGIN/CURRENT/END).
- Microsoft Learn — `GetStdHandle` (STD_INPUT_HANDLE etc.).
- Microsoft Learn — `winnt.h` reference (PAGE_NOACCESS=1,
  PAGE_READONLY=2, PAGE_READWRITE=4, PAGE_EXECUTE=16).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each constant is a nullary Process returning the synthesized integer.
The dispatcher routes `O_RDONLY from Syscall` etc. to these procs on
windows_arm64 targets via the bare-name pattern in force during Wave 1.
Wave 2 will rename to `windows_arm64_O_RDONLY` etc.; Wave 1 keeps the
bare form to match the still-bare dispatcher.

Numeric values are integer constants chosen per the design doc's
synthesis policy. The bodies are intentionally minimal (single Return).
Compiler inlining at the call site eliminates the call overhead.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; the compiler inlines them at every call site, so
the runtime cost is zero. Do not introduce computation or caching.
Caller code that compares against these constants (e.g. checking the
O_CREAT bit in a flags word) should fetch the constant once and cache
it locally in a tight loop, but the production codegen already does
this via SSA value-numbering.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a synthesized constant has no security state. Callers who
use O_* / MAP_* / PROT_* values in syscall_open / syscall_mmap /
syscall_mprotect on Windows MUST understand that the values are Win32
equivalents, not Linux values; passing a Linux-shaped flags integer
through to a Windows wrapper will produce incorrect dwDesiredAccess
or PAGE_* bits.

The MODE_* constants are advisory only on Windows (Windows file
permissions live in the security descriptor, not the integer mode);
callers SHOULD not rely on MODE_0644 producing world-readable
semantics on Windows — the api_create_file path ignores the mode
entirely. For correct cross-platform behaviour, set ACLs on Windows
via SECURITY_ATTRIBUTES; the synthesized MODE_* values are kept
solely for compile-time signature compatibility.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "windows_arm64_O_RDONLY" returns Integer:
    Return 2147483648  Note: GENERIC_READ = 0x80000000 (Windows synthesis)
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_O_WRONLY" returns Integer:
    Return 1073741824  Note: GENERIC_WRITE = 0x40000000 (Windows synthesis)
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_O_RDWR" returns Integer:
    Return 3221225472  Note: GENERIC_READ | GENERIC_WRITE = 0xC0000000
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_O_CREAT" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Semantic tag mapped to CREATE_ALWAYS in syscall_open
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_O_TRUNC" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Semantic tag mapped to TRUNCATE_EXISTING in syscall_open
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_O_APPEND" returns Integer:
    Return 4  Note: Semantic tag mapped to FILE_APPEND_DATA in syscall_open
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_PROT_NONE" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Windows synthesis: maps to PAGE_NOACCESS=1
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_PROT_READ" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Windows synthesis: maps to PAGE_READONLY=2
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_PROT_WRITE" returns Integer:
    Return 4  Note: Windows synthesis: maps to PAGE_READWRITE=4
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_PROT_EXEC" returns Integer:
    Return 16  Note: Windows synthesis: maps to PAGE_EXECUTE=16
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_MAP_SHARED" returns Integer:
    Return 67108864  Note: 0x4000000; synthesized; no direct Win32 equivalent
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_MAP_PRIVATE" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: Default Win32 VirtualAlloc behaviour is private
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_MAP_FIXED" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Synthesized; pass requested address to VirtualAlloc
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_MAP_ANONYMOUS" returns Integer:
    Return 64  Note: 0x40; synthesized; default VirtualAlloc behaviour
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: Matches Win32 FILE_BEGIN=0
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Matches Win32 FILE_CURRENT=1
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Matches Win32 FILE_END=2
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_STDIN_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return -10  Note: Matches Win32 STD_INPUT_HANDLE=-10
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_STDOUT_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return -11  Note: Matches Win32 STD_OUTPUT_HANDLE=-11
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_STDERR_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return -12  Note: Matches Win32 STD_ERROR_HANDLE=-12
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0o644 decimal; advisory only on Windows (ignored)
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0o755 decimal; advisory only on Windows (ignored)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
WINDOWS-SYNTHESIZED UNIX SYSCALL NUMBER SENTINELS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher requires 27 SYS_* nullary procs
that return the Unix-style syscall number for each operation. On
Windows there is no concept of a "Unix syscall number" — kernel
operations are reached through the Win32 API by symbol name, not via
a numeric index in a syscall table.

Per the P2-B design doc (line 323): "windows_x86_64_SYS_READ() returns
0 — the syscall number is meaningless on Windows; we return a sentinel
that the user-code never uses because the Windows syscall_read wrapper
bypasses the number." The same principle applies to windows_arm64.

Synthesis policy: each SYS_* proc returns -1 as a sentinel meaning
"syscall numbers are not applicable on Windows; use the matching
Win32 API wrapper instead." This differs from the design doc's
example (which used 0) because:

1. The Win32 API wrappers (`api_create_file`, `api_read_file`, etc.)
   exist as direct entry points; the high-level `syscall_*` wrappers
   in this file already route through `api_*` calls, NOT through the
   numeric `SYS_*` indirection.
2. The sentinel -1 makes accidental misuse loud: if any caller ever
   passes `SYS_READ()` into a `syscall_3()` call on Windows, the
   resulting syscall number -1 is rejected by every conceivable
   kernel32 entry, producing an immediate failure.
3. The value 0 happens to be a valid kernel32 import-thunk address
   (NULL pointer dereference) which could silently crash; -1 has no
   such collision.

Per @Reasoning on api_* additions above: Windows callers should route
through the explicit api_* surface (api_read_file, api_write_file,
api_create_file, etc.). The SYS_* sentinels exist only to satisfy the
dispatcher's compile-time bare-name link graph (P2-B Gate C / Gate D
closure).

The 27 names match exactly the dispatcher's published SYS_* surface:
SYS_BRK, SYS_CHDIR, SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME, SYS_CLOSE, SYS_CREAT, SYS_EXIT,
SYS_EXIT_GROUP, SYS_FSTAT, SYS_GETCWD, SYS_GETEGID, SYS_GETEUID,
SYS_GETGID, SYS_GETPID, SYS_GETPPID, SYS_GETUID, SYS_LSEEK,
SYS_LSTAT, SYS_MKDIR, SYS_MMAP, SYS_MUNMAP, SYS_OPEN, SYS_READ,
SYS_RMDIR, SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY, SYS_STAT, SYS_UNLINK, SYS_WRITE.

Mapping from SYS_* to the Win32 path that the matching syscall_*
wrapper routes through (informational; the SYS_* number itself is
never used on Windows):

| SYS_*                  | Win32 API path                            |
|------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
| SYS_READ               | ReadFile (api_read_file)                  |
| SYS_WRITE              | WriteFile (api_write_file)                |
| SYS_OPEN, SYS_CREAT    | CreateFileW (api_create_file)             |
| SYS_CLOSE              | CloseHandle (api_close_handle)            |
| SYS_LSEEK              | SetFilePointerEx (future FFI)             |
| SYS_STAT, SYS_LSTAT,
  SYS_FSTAT              | GetFileInformationByHandle (future FFI)   |
| SYS_MKDIR              | CreateDirectoryW (api_create_directory)   |
| SYS_RMDIR              | RemoveDirectoryW (api_remove_directory)   |
| SYS_UNLINK             | DeleteFileW (api_delete_file)             |
| SYS_CHDIR              | SetCurrentDirectoryW (future FFI)         |
| SYS_GETCWD             | GetCurrentDirectoryW (future FFI)         |
| SYS_MMAP, SYS_MUNMAP   | VirtualAlloc/VirtualFree (api_virtual_*)  |
| SYS_BRK                | (no equivalent; use VirtualAlloc)         |
| SYS_EXIT, SYS_EXIT_GROUP | TerminateProcess (api_terminate_process) |
| SYS_GETPID             | GetCurrentProcessId (api_get_current_process_id) |
| SYS_GETPPID            | (NT-only via NtQueryInformationProcess)   |
| SYS_GETUID, GETGID,
  GETEUID, GETEGID       | GetTokenInformation (future FFI)          |
| SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME      | QueryPerformanceCounter (api_query_*)     |
| SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY  | GetProcessAffinityMask (future FFI)       |

Sources: Microsoft Learn Win32 API reference (per-API page cited
above); P2-B design doc section "Special case: Windows synthesizes
Unix-style API" (line 317-325).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each SYS_* proc is a nullary Process returning -1. The dispatcher
resolves `SYS_READ from Syscall` to this proc on windows_arm64
targets via the bare-name pattern in force during Wave 1.

The bodies are intentionally minimal (single Return -1) because no
useful computation can be performed: the syscall-number concept does
not exist on Windows. Compiler inlining at the call site eliminates
the call overhead and the unused-value optimisation will fold away
the call entirely if the result is not consumed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single mov-immediate / return. Compiler inlines and folds. Zero
runtime cost. Callers should NOT use SYS_* values on Windows; the
correct path is the Win32-native api_* wrapper (api_read_file etc.).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning -1 has no security state. The sentinel value is chosen
specifically to fail loudly if accidentally fed into a syscall-by-
number dispatcher (no kernel32 thunk exists at address -1, so the
call crashes immediately rather than silently mis-dispatching).

This is a defence-in-depth measure: if a caller bug accidentally
routes a SYS_* value to syscall_N on Windows, the failure mode is
immediate-and-visible rather than silent-and-corrupting.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_READ" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_read_file (ReadFile); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_WRITE" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_write_file (WriteFile); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_OPEN" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_create_file (CreateFileW); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_CLOSE" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_close_handle (CloseHandle); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_CREAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_create_file with CREATE_ALWAYS; N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_STAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses GetFileInformationByHandle (future FFI); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_LSTAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows has no lstat (no symlink semantics); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_FSTAT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses GetFileInformationByHandle (future FFI); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_LSEEK" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses SetFilePointerEx (future FFI); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_FSYNC" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Windows has no direct fsync(2)-equivalent syscall in the NT
    syscall surface. The semantic equivalent — forcing a file's
    in-flight write buffers to physical storage — is exposed by
    the Win32 user-mode API as FlushFileBuffers, which internally
    invokes NtFlushBuffersFile. Because Runa's cross-platform
    dispatcher contract is "obtain the syscall number from
    SYS_FSYNC, then invoke syscall_1 with that number and the fd",
    and Windows fd semantics differ entirely from POSIX (HANDLE vs
    int), we return the canonical -1 sentinel to signal "this code
    path is not supported via raw syscall on this platform — use
    the higher-level api_flush_file_buffers wrapper instead". The
    arm64 Windows port shares this contract with windows_x86_64
    because the NT syscall surface is architecture-portable at the
    semantic level.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the -1 sentinel. Compile-time constant.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return; inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No security surface. The sentinel itself cannot be misused;
    callers are responsible for routing to api_flush_file_buffers
    which enforces the Windows ACL / HANDLE security model.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_IOCTL" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Windows has no direct ioctl(2)-equivalent syscall in the NT
    syscall surface. The semantic equivalent is the Win32
    DeviceIoControl API, which forwards to NtDeviceIoControlFile.
    Win32 IOCTL codes are CTL_CODE-encoded 32-bit values with no
    numeric mapping to POSIX request codes. The arm64 Windows
    port shares this contract with windows_x86_64 because the NT
    syscall surface is architecture-portable at the semantic level.
    Returns the -1 sentinel to signal "use api_device_io_control".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns the -1 sentinel. Compile-time constant.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Single integer return; inlinable.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No security surface. The sentinel itself cannot be misused;
    callers route to api_device_io_control which enforces the
    Windows ACL / driver-IOCTL access model.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_MMAP" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_virtual_alloc (VirtualAlloc); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_MUNMAP" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_virtual_free (VirtualFree); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_BRK" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows has no brk equivalent; use VirtualAlloc; N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_EXIT" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_terminate_process (TerminateProcess); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_EXIT_GROUP" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_terminate_process; SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_MKDIR" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_create_directory (CreateDirectoryW); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_RMDIR" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_remove_directory (RemoveDirectoryW); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_UNLINK" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses api_delete_file (DeleteFileW); SYS number N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_CHDIR" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses SetCurrentDirectoryW (future FFI); N/A
End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_GETCWD" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses GetCurrentDirectoryW (future FFI); N/A
