End Process

Process called "windows_arm64_SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: Windows uses GetProcessAffinityMask (future FFI); N/A
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
WINDOWS-SYNTHESIZED GENERIC SYSCALL DISPATCHER SENTINELS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher exposes 7 generic syscall_N
entry points (syscall_0 through syscall_6) for direct numeric
syscall invocation with N arguments. These are the lowest level of
the dispatcher hierarchy — every higher-level wrapper (syscall_read,
syscall_open, etc.) routes through one of these.

On Linux/BSD/Darwin the syscall_N bodies issue the platform-specific
syscall instruction (`syscall` on x86_64, `svc #0` on ARM64, `swi
#0` on ARM32) with the syscall number in the platform-specified
register. On Windows there is no equivalent — kernel32 functions are
called by symbol via `bl <SymbolName>`, not by a numeric index.

Per the P2-B design doc Decision 4 (line 154): Windows routes all
kernel operations through named Win32 API wrappers (`api_create_file`,
`api_read_file`, etc.) instead of synthetic syscall numbers. The
syscall_N entry points on Windows are therefore sentinels that
return -1: they exist to satisfy the dispatcher's compile-time
bare-name link graph closure (Gate C / Gate D of the audit) but they
are never called by correct Windows code. The high-level Windows
syscall_* wrappers (syscall_read, syscall_write, etc.) bypass
syscall_N entirely and call api_* directly.

Synthesis policy: each syscall_N returns -1. The sentinel value -1
ensures that any accidental caller that ignores the documented
Windows-portability requirement and attempts a numeric-syscall
dispatch on Windows gets an immediate, visible failure rather than
a silent miscompilation. NULL (0) can alias to a valid kernel32
import-thunk address in some configurations; -1 has no such collision.

Sources:
- P2-B design doc line 154 (Decision 4: Windows uses Win32 API
  symbols, not synthetic syscall numbers).
- P2-B design doc line 317-325 (Special case: Windows synthesizes
  Unix-style API).
- Microsoft Learn: "There is no documented Win32 user-mode entry
  point for issuing NT system calls by number" (kernel32 routine
  documentation set; the NT system service table is undocumented
  and Microsoft explicitly reserves the right to renumber per
  Windows version, which is why we avoid this path entirely on
  Windows ARM64 — Decision 4 rationale).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each syscall_N proc takes (syscall_number, arg1, ..., argN) per the
dispatcher's contract, ignores all arguments, and returns -1.

The bodies are intentionally minimal. Inline assembly is NOT used
because there is no Windows ARM64 kernel-entry instruction to issue
(unlike the Linux ARM64 `svc #0` pattern); the Windows kernel is
reached only via kernel32.dll exports, which are named, not
numbered. Issuing `svc` on Windows ARM64 from user mode triggers
SEH ACCESS_VIOLATION because the system service table is not mapped
into the user address space.

The dispatcher's idx=15 leg routes through these procs at compile
time (link graph closure); at run time, the high-level
windows_arm64-side wrappers (syscall_read etc.) bypass them.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Single mov-immediate / return. Compiler inlines and folds. Zero
runtime cost. These wrappers SHOULD NOT appear on any Windows hot
path; if a profile shows time spent in syscall_N on Windows, the
caller is using the wrong API (use api_* directly).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning -1 has no security state. The sentinel choice is
defence-in-depth: any caller that bypasses the documented Windows
contract and attempts a numeric syscall gets an immediate -1
failure, which fails loud rather than silent.

These wrappers do NOT trap into the kernel, do NOT touch any
kernel object, do NOT mutate any process state. They are pure
functions returning -1. The Windows ARM64 user-mode permissions
model is unaffected.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "windows_arm64_syscall_0" takes syscall_number as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Windows has no numeric-syscall path; use api_* wrappers directly.
    syscall_number: ignored
    Returns: -1 (operation not supported on Windows)
    :End Note
    Return -1
End Process

